  "texts": [
    "Both these global and the local constraint-based algorithms make one further assumption known as causal sufficiency, which is of importance if we wish to interpret the BNs causally.",
    "This assumption means there are no latent (unmeasured) variables that would affect the causal relationships.",
    "For example, variables that are a common cause of two or more of the measured variables X, which are widely known as latent confounders.",
    "The SGS algorithm (Spirtes et al. 1990) is rather inefficient but is of interest since many constraint-based algorithms build upon its approach.",
    "SGS relies on two key theorems derived from the definition of Bayesian Networks (Verma and Pearl 1990) that apply to faithful and causally sufficient BNs:"
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The SGS algorithm (Spirtes et al. 1990) is rather inefficient but is of interest since many constraint-based algorithms build upon its approach.",
